sentence: Home improvement warehouse operators The Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ) and Lowe's Companies, Inc. ( LOW ) both saw their earnings estimates cut on Tuesday by analysts at Goldman Sachs.
The firm lowered its estimates for HD due to a lower sales outlook, and cut its price target for the stock to $34.
That new target would represent a 22% upside to the stock's Friday closing price of $27.76.
Goldman also maintained its "Buy" rating on Home Depot.
As for Lowe's, the firm cut its estimates through 2012 on expectations of lower sales in the coming quarters.
Goldman left its "Neutral" rating on LOW unchanged, but set a new $25 price target.
That new target would represent a 23% upside to the stock's Friday closing price of $20.27.
Home Depot shares rose 44 cents, or +1.6%, while Lowe's shares fell 10 cents, or -0.5%, in premarket trading Tuesday.
Shares of HD have a dividend yield of 3.39%, based on Friday's closing stock price of $27.76.
Shares of LOW have a dividend yield of 2.17%, based on Friday's closing stock price of $20.27.
